<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/52711508-max-lauber"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1455571498i/52711508._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/52711508-max-lauber">Max Lauber</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">You&apos;re definitely making a good point. The other part that bugged me was that &quot;Error Bot&quot; that is programmed to switch letters with the same frequency<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">You're definitely making a good point. The other part that bugged me was that "Error Bot" that is programmed to switch letters with the same frequency as he found in his data. Obviously, the Bot's output would contain the same errors. The much more relevant question (to see whether Freud was right) would be whether switches that can be read sexually occur with a higher or lower frequency than those that are not sexually connoted. Does anyone know whether Seth's Freud research appears only in the book? Or whether this data is available somewhere?<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
